  "prompt": "What is the best way to clear an overgrown garden with mostly grass and weeds without using chemicals?",
  "response": "Here are several effective methods to clear an overgrown garden without chemicals:\n\n1. Manual Removal\n- Use a lawn mower or string trimmer to cut down tall grass and weeds\n- Hand-pull weeds, ensuring you remove the roots\n- Use a garden hoe to dig out stubborn weeds\n- Wear gloves and comfortable clothing\n\n2. Sheet Mulching (Layering)\n- Cover the area with cardboard or several layers of newspaper\n- Add a thick layer of organic mulch (wood chips, straw, or compost) on top\n- This method smothers existing vegetation and creates a new growing surface\n- Takes several weeks to months to break down vegetation\n\n3. Solarization\n- Cover the area with clear plastic sheeting\n- Secure edges to trap heat\n- Leave in place for 4-6 weeks during hot summer months\n- Heat will kill grass, weeds, and seeds\n\n4. Organic Ground Cover\n- Plant ground cover plants that will naturally suppress weeds\n- Examples: clover, creeping thyme, or native ground covers\n\n5. Repeated Cutting\n- Consistently mow or cut vegetation\n- Prevents weeds from going to seed\n- Weakens root systems over time\n\nChoose the method best suited to your specific garden size and conditions.",
